FR940804-2-00175 FR940804-2-00093 Application for Approval of Discontinuance or Modification of a Railroad Signal System or Relief From the Requirements of 49 CFR Part 236 Pursuant to 49 CFR Part 235 and 49 U.S.C. App. 26, the following railroads have petitioned the Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) seeking approval for the discontinuance or modification of the signal system or relief from the requirements of 49 CFR Part 236 as detailed below. Block Signal Application (BS&hyph;AP)&hyph;No. 3300 Applicant: Southern Pacific Lines, Mr. J.A. Turner, Engineer_Signals, Southern Pacific Building, One Market Plaza, San Francisco, California 94105. The Southern Pacific Lines seeks approval of the proposed conversion of the manual interlocking system to a traffic control system, at Grant Tower, milepost WA&hyph;745.4, near Salt Lake City, Utah, Rocky Mountain Region, Subdivision 7. The reason given for the proposed changes is to enhance safety by having the dispatcher use only one set of operating rules for the territory under his control. BS&hyph;AP&hyph;No. 3301 Applicant: Southern Pacific Lines, Mr. J.A. Turner, Engineer_Signals, Southern Pacific Building, One Market Plaza, San Francisco, California 94105. The Southern Pacific Lines seeks approval of the proposed conversion of the manual interlocking system to a traffic control system, at Tower 112, milepost THE&hyph;211.0, near San Antonio, Texas, Gulf Coast Region, Del Rio District. The reason given for the proposed changes is to enhance safety by having the dispatcher use only one set of operating rules for the territory under his control. BS&hyph;AP&hyph;No. 3302 Applicant: Southern Pacific Lines, Mr. J.A. Turner, Engineer_Signals, Southern Pacific Building, One Market Plaza, San Francisco, California 94105. The Southern Pacific Lines seeks approval of the proposed conversion of the manual interlocking system to a traffic control system, at Becks, milepost WA&hyph;748.7, near Salt Lake City, Utah, Rocky Mountain Region, Subdivision 7. The reason given for the proposed changes is to enhance safety by having the dispatcher use only one set of operating rules for the territory under his control. BS&hyph;AP&hyph;No. 3303 Applicant: Union Pacific Railroad Company, Mr. P.M. Abaray, Chief Engineer_Signals, 1416 Dodge Street, Room 1000, Omaha, Nebraska 68179.
